{
  "doc_id": "49590",
  "text": "Vitiligo is a disorder of pigmentation and little is known about its aetiology. One of the most popular hypotheses considers vitiligo as an autoimmune disease. Previous investigations have proven that the anti-melanocyte antibody, which destroys the skin melanocyte, is one of the important autoantibodies causing vitiligo [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . The important antigens detected in vitiligo patients include, but may not be limited to, tyrosinase (5), tyrosinase-related protein-1 (TRP-1) (7), tyrosinaserelated protein-2 (TRP-2) (6), Pmel17 [CITATION_4] , the transcription factor SOX10 (8) and MCHR1 [CITATION_5] . Of these autoantigens, McHR1 is the sole antigen on the cell surface, although antibodies in vitiligo patients are most commonly directed against melanocyte antigens on the cellular membrane (4).",
